ompensated) and unacceptable (uncompensated) risk.The Appeal of Insurance traces the ways in which insurance, over the past three centuries, has grown in concert with a clientele largely of its own making. Drawing on the fields of history, sociology, criminology and economics, these essays break new ground in insurance studies by illuminating the dialectical relationship between the expansion of the insurance business and the public demand for economic and social security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInsurancexHistory. 0aInsurance. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aAlborn, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Greg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnderson, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Geoffrey W. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEricson, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLengwiler, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFall, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPons, Jerònia Pons, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenhaft, Eve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulenburg, J.-Matthias Graf von der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomann, Christian , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avon der Schulenburg, J. Matthias-Graf, eeditor.4edt4ht